occurrenceRemarks: On a dead ash tree.

Emerald Ash Borers moved through our area, and within about two years, most of the ash trees were gone from our woods. There was a huge ash (green or white) at the head of the trail at the Campbell County Environmental Education Center, and I paused to mourn its passing. Then I saw the flickers of green as the emerging ash borers flew up from the remnants. Note that about 6 feet of the trunk was left in place. If you must cut a tree, leaving a bit of the trunk (as much as possible, but short enough not to be a falling hazard) is a great way to support your local wildlife. It's still useful to insects, fungi, woodpeckers, and critters in want of a perch.
